  "text": "Using sector (industry) level panel data from 26 countries, our identification strategy adapts the approach in [CITATION_1] -hereafter referred to as RZ1998-which is based on the insight that changes in the supply of finance are more likely to affect industries \"inherently\" more dependent on external financing. The impact of the financial crisis is identified by measuring how the association between aggregate credit and employment during the crisis years varied across industries with high and low inherent financial dependence. Exploiting country and time level variation in the decline in aggregate credit during the crisis years, and industry-level variation in the sensitivity to external finance, this \"differences-in-differences\" method disentangles the effects of the credit crunch from those of other macroeconomic shocks. 5 It is important to do so because the banking crises in Europe occurred during a global economic slowdown which could have affected labor demand through other channels, such as a decline in export demand.",
